WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:04.700
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:18.070 --> 00:00:20.690
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Peterson:
Good afternoon everyone.

00:00:20.690 --> 00:00:23.990
If I could ask you to take a seat.

00:00:23.990 --> 00:00:26.130
My name is Betsy Peterson.

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:29.190
I'm the Director of the American
Folklife Center here at the Library

00:00:29.190 --> 00:00:33.770
of Congress and on behalf of the
staff, I want to welcome you today

00:00:33.770 --> 00:00:38.430
for what is the latest presentation
of our Botkin Lecture Series

00:00:38.430 --> 00:00:42.330
and I should say this is the
first presentation of 2016

00:00:42.330 --> 00:00:45.230
and it's a very special
presentation.

00:00:45.230 --> 00:00:51.540
The Botkin Series for the
American Folklife Center allows us

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:52.840
to do a few things.

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:56.740
Most importantly, it allows
us to present the latest

00:00:56.740 --> 00:01:02.000
and best scholarship in folklore,
ethnomusicology, oral history,

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.660
and cultural heritage
studies of all kinds.

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:10.770
But also is an important strategy
for us regarding acquisitions.

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:15.810
These lectures are
tape-recorded and will become part

00:01:15.810 --> 00:01:19.730 position:56%
of our permanent collections at the
library, so if you want to come back

00:01:19.730 --> 00:01:23.810
and listen to it you can, but it
also will eventually be prepared

00:01:23.810 --> 00:01:26.570 position:56%
for webcast so that it can be shared

00:01:26.570 --> 00:01:29.590
with Internet patrons
throughout the world

00:01:29.590 --> 00:01:32.600
who obviously cannot make it here.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:37.840
So with that said or that caveat,
if you have a cell phone turned

00:01:37.840 --> 00:01:40.620
on please take a moment
to turn it off.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:46.190
And now to the special part, this
is a special lecture today for us

00:01:46.190 --> 00:01:50.580
because it allows us to
celebrate one of our partners

00:01:50.580 --> 00:01:54.280
and collaborators, The
Country Dance and Song Society

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:57.920
who are celebrating their
centennial this year.

00:01:57.920 --> 00:02:02.390
Our correspondence files at the
American Folklife Center are full

00:02:02.390 --> 00:02:06.850
of letters dating back to 1974
between the two organizations

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:11.460
and over the years, has
donated books to our collections

00:02:11.460 --> 00:02:13.960
and we've collected a
full run of the magazine

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.050
"Country Dance and Song."

00:02:16.050 --> 00:02:21.420
We helped plan the move of CDSS's
library from a private home

00:02:21.420 --> 00:02:23.820
to the University of New Hampshire

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:29.080
and CDSS awarded AFC a grant
a few years ago to help

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:33.710
in the digitization of our James
Madison Carpenter collection

00:02:33.710 --> 00:02:36.620
which was terrific and
we're so thankful and CDSS

00:02:36.620 --> 00:02:42.240 position:56%
and AFC have collaborated on several
successful lecture and dance events

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:44.830
over the years celebrating
the acquisitions

00:02:44.830 --> 00:02:47.990
of the Anthony Grant
Barrand Collection.

00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:51.410
So continuing in this
long tradition,

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:56.470
when I first came here a few
years ago, I was pleased to meet

00:02:56.470 --> 00:03:01.010 position:56%
with CDSS's Executive Director Rima
Dael here at the Library of Congress

00:03:01.010 --> 00:03:04.550
about how the American Folklife
Center could be involved

00:03:04.550 --> 00:03:08.880
and could support the
centennial celebration of CDSS

00:03:08.880 --> 00:03:12.660
and to plan today's lecture
and dance demonstration.

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:15.510
So let's just take a moment
to give a round of applause

00:03:15.510 --> 00:03:18.510
to Country Dance and Song Society.

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:25.620
[ Applause ]

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:27.830
And here's to another 100 years,

00:03:27.830 --> 00:03:31.660
though we probably won't be
there then, but anyway now,

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:35.870
allow me to introduce today's
speaker Dr. Graham Christian.

00:03:35.870 --> 00:03:39.320
Graham Christian is a dance
historian, English dance leader,

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:44.370 position:56%
choreographer, director and
musician for Amherst, Massachusetts.

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:47.990
He holds a doctorate in 17th
century English literature

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:51.360
from the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:55.290
and he is also a librarian who
holds a master's degree in library

00:03:55.290 --> 00:04:01.350
and information science from
Simmons College; a Renaissance man.

00:04:01.350 --> 00:04:05.700
In addition to having authored
"The Playford Assembly," which were

00:04:05.700 --> 00:04:09.980
for sale out there today and
I think have sold out in fact,

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:12.570
he writes the Dance History
column, "Tell Me More,"

00:04:12.570 --> 00:04:16.690
for the CDSS newsletter
and appears as caller

00:04:16.690 --> 00:04:21.100 position:56%
for English country dances all over
the U.S. and is a frequent presenter

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:24.670
at academic conferences
lecturing and talking

00:04:24.670 --> 00:04:26.710
about the history of social dance.

00:04:26.710 --> 00:04:33.440 position:56%
And I also want to welcome and
thank him, because he donated a copy

00:04:33.440 --> 00:04:36.410
of "The Playford Assembly"
to our collections today

00:04:36.410 --> 00:04:39.170
so we're very appreciative of that.

00:04:39.170 --> 00:04:42.110
But with so with all of that
said now, please join me

00:04:42.110 --> 00:04:47.510
in welcoming today's Botkin
lecturer, Dr. Graham Christian.

00:04:47.510 --> 00:04:57.040
[ Applause ]

